{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 After reviewing both experts\rquote  methodologies, we conclude that Black\u8211\'3fScholes is a more credible stock option valuation method than the Growth Model. Unlike Mr. Rowley\rquote s Growth Model, Black\u8211\'3fScholes accounts for the effects of dividends and volatility on the stock options\rquote  values. Moreover, generally accepted accounting principles support the use of Black\u8211\'3fScholes for valuing stock options. For example, paragraph 19 of SFAS No. 123 requires for financial reporting purposes that companies use a fair value method of accounting, such as Black\u8211\'3fScholes, to estimate the companies\rquote  stock option expenses.
